{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together regardless of which microservice emitted them.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is typically between JSON parsing/normalization and correlation logic. A unit test of only the grouping function can miss real mismatches in how different service log schemas are mapped into the common trace-ID field.","test_description":"Run the ingest pipeline end-to-end in-process (no external network) with mixed JSON logs from multiple service formats that share trace IDs, then assert one correlated group per trace ID across all emitters.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Clock-skew handling is usually implemented in timeline assembly, not just a raw sort function. Wiring multiple modules (timestamp parsing, normalization, ordering, render model) is needed to catch boundary bugs.","test_description":"Feed correlated multi-service logs with controlled timestamp offsets (including +/-500ms skew and edge cases near the threshold) through the timeline-building pipeline and assert deterministic final ordering rules are respected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures often come from how baseline windows, percentile computation, and report flagging are connected. A pure unit test of percentile math may pass while the integrated detector fails to flag.","test_description":"Execute anomaly detection on representative log batches with known baseline and injected high-latency tail so true p99 exceeds 3x baseline; assert anomaly flag presence in the generated report payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON log entries are skipped without crashing the pipeline, and the count of skipped entries is reported.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior spans parser error handling plus pipeline control flow and metrics/report counters. Mocking parser outcomes can hide real decode exceptions and counter propagation bugs.","test_description":"Run ingest on a mixed stream of valid and malformed JSON entries through real parsing code, assert pipeline completes without crash, valid entries are processed, and skipped-entry count equals malformed-entry count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Throughput/backpressure and drop behavior depend on real runtime characteristics (thread scheduling, queues, I/O, process limits). In-process mocks or synthetic stubs can mask bottlenecks and drops.","test_description":"Run a load test against the real executable/service with a real log producer generating 10,000 entries/sec for a sustained interval; measure ingest lag and processed-vs-sent counts, and fail on any sustained backlog growth or dropped entries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
